"It's important to learn how to grow your own food because good food sustains us together as a community. A diverse community will be more successful and interesting than a monoculture."  -Elena Greenberg, Slow Food USA Ark of Taste gardener from Arizona.

According to Feeding America, an estimated 25-40% of food grown, processed and transported in the U.S. will never be consumed. Here are three tips from Slow Food USA to minimize food waste in our home kitchens:  1. Cook with the kitchen scraps that come from prepping ingredients. Produce scraps are habitually tossed in the bin, yet they make for excellent aromatic garnish for stock. Diced small and sauteed, they can make a nutritious filling in chili, tomato sauce or risotto!   2. Compost. Transform food waste into a nutritious component for healthy soil. If you don’t garden, find a neighbor gardener or nearby farmer who may be happy to receive your bucket of collected kitchen scraps and coffee grounds.  3. Can and preserve. Making pickles, sauces or jams is an excellent way to use produce that you get in bulk when it’s in season or on sale.
